scx_lavd: Scale the deadline compete window by the oversubscription ratio

The constant LAVD_DL_COMPETE_WINDOW head start disables deadline aging
whenever a task's deadline delta is smaller than the window: the enqueued
vtime lands behind cur_logical_clk, which then cannot advance
(advance_cur_logical_clk() returns early on vlc <= clc), and ordering
degenerates to a pure deadline-delta ranking with no aging. Under heavy
oversubscription of similar tasks this starves whichever task the pipeline
is currently blocked on and serializes the whole workload.

This is the root cause of issue #3303: hackbench -g 8 -l 10000 regressed
~50% between v1.0.19 and v1.0.20. Bisected to a8a25fcb ("Increase greedy
factor in deadline calculation") and isolated to the
LAVD_DL_COMPETE_WINDOW change alone (300ms vs 5ms: 26.0s vs 17.4s on a
4-thread cpuset, n=10).

A plain revert is not acceptable: the enlarged window is what protects
latency-critical tasks against a herd of similar-deadline tasks (the
commit's stated fork-bomb scenario). Measured: reverting the constant
takes fork-storm schbench wake p99 from 76us to 607us.

Instead, scale the window by how oversubscribed the system is: grant the
full window while the runnable backlog fits the active CPUs (bit-identical
to current behavior at light load), and shrink it by nr_active/nr_queued
beyond that so aging resumes as the backlog grows. This uses the same
normalization calc_sys_time_slice() and advance_cur_logical_clk() already
apply, and the same nr_queued <= nr_active boundary as can_boost_slice().

Measured (AMD 7950X; "real-8CPU" = 24 CPUs offlined, single-LLC 4c/8t):
- hackbench -g8 -l10000 (4-thread cpuset, n=10): 25.54 +/- 0.37 s ->
  17.43 +/- 0.04 s (EEVDF reference: 16.9 s)
- fork-storm schbench wake p99 (n=6): 73-85us, unchanged from the
  constant window (plain revert: 607us; EEVDF: 3604us)
- interactive harness (6 CPU hogs + schbench): wake p99 -36% (p<0.001),
  sched-messaging -13% (p<0.001); real-8CPU messaging -20% (p=0.002)
  with wake p99 unregressed
- powersave mode: messaging -14% (p=0.001), nothing regressed

Per-task criticality-scaled windows were tried and rejected: scaling from
avg_lat_cri regresses interactive wake p99 65-91% (the average is
dominated by the frequently-scheduling tasks themselves), and gating on
thr_lat_cri loses the fork-storm protection (the threshold rides within a
hair of max under a storm). The queue-depth scaling keeps the window
uniform across tasks, so it changes only the aging regime, never the
relative order of same-epoch enqueues.

Fixes: #3303
